caption: Good sushi.  But the flooring, that appeared to be linoleum, was actually carpeting!  That has been worn down to a dull shine!  Very sketch.  Just because you cater to college students, doesn’t mean you can at least update your tired, worn flooring.  It felt sticky and greasy underfoot.  Almost as if I was at a movie theater.  Looked gross, actually. Keep it simple on the sushi.  Distracting me with flaming sushi rolls only hides the lack of freshness.

I really like Ami. It is my go-to place in Bloomington to get sushi but it also has an extensive menu that offers other fine options. Yes, I got better sushi at the Tsukiji Market but for a small college town in the US Midwest, the quality is very good. The sashimi regular is always fresh and for those who want something cooked, I highly recommend the tonkatsu,which is a great value for the price. Service has been consistently good both in takeout and dine-in (pre-pandemic).

Average tasting sushi place. The salmon sashimi was very sad looking and tasted terrible.....should have sent it back and thought perhaps the server would notice that I didn’t eat the sashimi but they didn’t. The key ingredient for good sushi is properly cooked rice...not here....the rice was too dense and tasteless, making the rolls and nigiri taste pretty below average. The gyoza 🥟 were okay.  The shrimp tempura in the roll was cold and seemed like was fried a long time ago.  There are many better sushi options in the area....save your money by not going here.

I hadn't eaten here in years, but I decided to takeout sushi last night. The sushi was disappointing compared to other sushi spots in Bloomington. The fish didn't seem very fresh and one of the rolls (spicy tuna) tasted very fishy. The two spicy rolls I ordered were not spicy at all; I think the spicy sauce was accidentally left out. The shrimp tempura in the rolls tasted bland and a bit soggy and again, it seems the sauce was left off. I also had the ultimate rainbow chef's roll which was the best one out of the ones I ordered, but the quality just wasn't worth the price. All in all, I wouldn't order sushi from here again as the taste and quality were subpar.

We ordered through a third party delivery services who delivered the wrong food. The Ami staff was so gracious and understanding; they offered to remake our order free of charge if the delivery company would come get it. I said I would go instead, not wanting to trust the delivery company again. When I arrived, the Ami staff apologized for the situation multiple times. I offered to pay for the replacement because it wasn't their fault and I didn't want them to lose money because of it. They gave me a 50% discount anyways, remade our order quickly, and then left two free roll cards with my order when I took it home. The ramen was a broth with the flavor of Shoyu, chashu pork and heat at the back.  I was so indecisive I didn't know what to order, but I love tuna so the server recommended I get the spicy tuna. I also asked for a suggestion on what to order as far as salmon  , the server  said people love the spicy salmon rolls so I got an order of that as well.  I was thinking I was getting a basic order or spicy tuna&salmon rolls, but to my surprise the rolls were fresh and almost like they  had cream cheese in them.   I recommend  sushi lovers try Ami, there's also a good selection of popular Korean dishes such as ; Japchae, Bulgogi, and bibimbap. One of the better places to eat in Bloomington, in my opinion. I know people like to brag about the variety in here,but honestly what's good is variety if it's all disgusting or tasteless? Being a person from below the Mason Dixon, I prefer my food to be well flavored--not to salty, perfectly seasoned. Not may restaurants in Bloomington can live up to that level of food preparation--even some of the chain restaurants. However, in this city full of bland, badly seasoned and sometimes down right awful (several of the Chinese restaurants) Ami stands out as a champion and reign supreme (when I'm not in the mood to cook). The service varies, it just depends on who's working--some of the waitress are really nice others just there for the paycheck, like another establishment (well except maybe Hooters, as long as there is at least one male at the table).

I don't know why its called Domo on here, its Ami Resturant. They hours posted on the door, which was propped open said open till 10PM.  It was printed on a piece of paper because it had changed, so it was supposed to be the update info.  I walked in at 9:45 wanting a carryout order, they said the kitchen closed at 9:40.  Don't post your hours as closing at 10PM when you close at 9:40, post that as your hours of closing.  If your going to be open till 10, keep the kitchen open till 10 and close down after that.  Probably some employees slacking off just trying to close down early.  Either way, thats awful service and that was the 1 and only time Ill ever waste my time going there.
